\f0\fs24 \cf0 The hagazussa, the fence-sitter, between the wilderness and the village, \'93was a being who participated in both worlds\'94 (McKenna 1993, 117). Most mythological canons have liminal deities such as hagazussa, including liminal deities separating order (village) from chaos (wilderness). Osiris was the liminal deity of Egyptian mythology. Osiris presided over the Underworld, a duty which required him to judge the dead, thus making the border between order and chaos selectively permeable instead of open. Osiris was also the flood god, another liminal myth, since floods create chaos for those caught in their path. In Haitian Vodou, one finds Legba occupying this role. Legba is the intermediary between the spirit world, and the living. He judges whether or not to allow the living to speak with those residing in the spirit world. \
